# Security Practices

## Input Validation
- Validate ALL external input at handler boundary (`c.Bind`, struct tags, `validator`)
- Sanitize user input before logging (prevent log injection)
- Limit request body size and query parameter length (Echo middleware)

## Authentication & Authorization
- Validate tokens/sessions on protected routes via `internal/middlewares/` (auth, CSRF where applicable)
- OIDC flows: follow existing patterns in `internal/handlers/oidc.go`, `internal/services/oidc.go`, `internal/auth/`
- Service layer must NOT read `echo.Context` — pass `context.Context` and typed user/session IDs
- Federation (Google, etc.): verify state/nonce and provider tokens per existing federation services

## Secrets Management
- Never hardcode secrets — use `internal/config/` env-backed `Config`
- Never commit `cmd/server/.env`, credentials, API keys, or private keys
- Use different secrets per environment (dev/qa/prod)
- MFA/WebAuthn secrets: use `internal/crypto/` helpers; never log TOTP seeds or challenge payloads

## SQL Injection Prevention
- Use GORM/parameterized queries — never concatenate user input into SQL
- Validate dynamic identifiers if unavoidable

## API Security
- HTTPS in production; security headers via `internal/middlewares/security.go`
- CORS: don't use `*` in production — follow `internal/middlewares/cors.go`
- CSRF (`internal/middlewares/csrf.go`) — token via `X-CSRF-Token` header / `csrf_token` cookie
- **CSRF skipped paths** (do not require token): `/api/v1/register`, `/login`, `/refresh`, `/logout`; `/api/v1/webauthn/*`, `/api/v1/mfa/*`; root `/token`, `/authorize`, `/userinfo`, `/.well-known/*`, `/oidc/federation/*`
- **CSRF enforced**: `/oidc/login` (browser OIDC password form) — extend skip list only with good reason
- Log authentication failures with source IP; mask tokens and PII in logs

## Data Protection
- TLS for all network communication
- Mask emails, tokens, session IDs in logs
- Handle PII according to applicable regulations

## Error Handling
- Never expose stack traces or internal errors to clients
- Use `AppError` / `ErrorHandler` for consistent, safe responses
- Don't leak DB schema or internal architecture in error messages
